          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In the clinical case of obstructed labour, which primary function of the female </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In the clinical case of obstructed labour, which primary function of the female pelvis is compromised when the bony outlet is contracted?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Support of abdominal viscera from below</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The pelvis does support viscera from below, but this function is unaffected by a narrow bony outlet. The problem is that the birth canal dimensions are too small for the foetal head.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Formation of the birth canal for vaginal delivery</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The female pelvis forms the bony birth canal through which the baby must pass. When the outlet is contracted, the foetal head cannot descend, necessitating caesarean section.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Transmission of body weight to the lower limbs</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Weight transmission occurs through the hip joints and is a separate mechanical function of the pelvis, unrelated to obstructed labour.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Attachment site for the pelvic diaphragm muscles</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>While the levator ani and coccygeus attach to pelvic bones, their attachment is not what narrows the bony outlet in a contracted pelvis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The birth canal function is compromised. In a contracted pelvis, the bony outlet is too narrow for the foetal head to pass through, requiring operative delivery."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The female pelvis forms the birth canal, and a contracted bony outlet prevents vaginal delivery of the foetal head."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
