          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>During hysterectomy, the uterine artery must be ligated medial to which structur</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During hysterectomy, the uterine artery must be ligated medial to which structure to avoid inadvertent injury?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ovarian artery</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The ovarian artery descends via the suspensory ligament of the ovary, well away from the uterine artery's crossing point two centimetres from the cervix.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ureter</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The uterine artery crosses the ureter two centimetres lateral to the cervix — remembered as 'water under the bridge.' Ligation must be placed medial to the ureter to protect it from injury.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Internal pudendal artery</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The internal pudendal artery exits below piriformis and reaches the perineum via the lesser sciatic foramen. It is not in the surgical field near the cervix.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Obturator nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The obturator nerve runs along the lateral pelvic wall and enters the obturator canal, far from the uterine artery–ureter crossing at the cervix.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The ureter is at risk. The uterine artery crosses it two centimetres lateral to the cervix. Surgeons must ligate the artery medial to this crossing to prevent ureteric damage."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The uterine artery crosses above the ureter 2 cm from the cervix — 'water under the bridge.' Ligating medial to the ureter avoids ureteric injury."
                }
              ],
