          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Internal haemorrhoids that lie above the pectinate line are typically painless b</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Internal haemorrhoids that lie above the pectinate line are typically painless because:</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>They drain via the inferior rectal vein into the inferior vena cava</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This describes external haemorrhoids, not internal. Internal haemorrhoids drain via the superior rectal vein into the portal system. Venous drainage pattern does not determine pain sensation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>They are supplied exclusively by sympathetic nerve fibres</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Both sympathetic and parasympathetic fibres innervate the rectum above the pectinate line. These are visceral fibres that transmit vague sensations like distension, but the critical point is the absence of somatic pain fibres.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Somatic innervation is absent above the pectinate line</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The mucosa above the pectinate line receives only visceral (autonomic) innervation, which does not transmit sharp, localised pain. Below the line, the inferior rectal nerve provides somatic sensation, making external haemorrhoids painful.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The rectal mucosa above the pectinate line lacks sensory nerve endings entirely</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The mucosa above the pectinate line does have sensory endings — they are visceral and transmit sensations like distension. What it lacks is somatic innervation that transmits sharp, well-localised pain.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Internal haemorrhoids are painless because somatic nerve fibres are absent above the pectinate line. Only visceral innervation is present, which does not transmit sharp pain."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. Somatic innervation is absent above the pectinate line, so internal haemorrhoids are painless. Below it, the inferior rectal nerve provides somatic pain sensation."
                }
              ],
